HEADWORD: Sit
<hw>Sit</hw> <pr>(s⟦icr⟧t)</pr>, <def><pos>obs. 3d pers. sing.
pres.</pos> of <er>Sit</er>, for <xex>sitteth</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sit
<hw>Sit</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos>
<conjf>Sat</conjf> <pr>(s⟦acr⟧t)</pr> (<conjf>Sate</conjf>
<pr>(s⟦amac⟧t)</pr>, <mark>archaic</mark>); <pos>p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Sat</conjf> (<conjf>Sitten</conjf> <pr>(s⟦icr⟧t"t'n)</pr>,
<mark>obs.</mark>); <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sitting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>sitten</ets>, AS.
<ets>sittan</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>sittian</ets>, OFries.
<ets>sitta</ets>, D. <ets>zitten</ets>, G. <ets>sitzen</ets>, OHG.
<ets>sizzen</ets>, Icel. <ets>sitja</ets>, SW. <ets>sitta</ets>, Dan.
<ets>sidde</ets>, Goth. <ets>sitan</ets>, Russ. <ets>sidiete</ets>, L.
<ets>sedere</ets>, Gr. <grk>'e`zesqai</grk>, Skr. <ets>sad</ets>.
⟦root⟧154. Cf. <er>Assess</er>,<er>Assize</er>, <er>Cathedral</er>,
<er>Chair</er>, <er>Dissident</er>, <er>Excise</er>, <er>Insidious</er>,
<er>Possess</er>, <er>Reside</er>, <er>Sanhedrim</er>,
<er>S⟦eacute⟧ance</er>, <er>Seat</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, <er>Sedate</er>,
<er>4th Sell</er>, <er>Siege</er>, <er>Session</er>, <er>Set</er>,
<pos>v. t.</pos>, <er>Sizar</er>, <er>Size</er>,
<er>Subsidy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To rest upon the haunches, or
the lower extremity of the trunk of the body; -- said of human beings,
and sometimes of other animals; <as>as, to <ex>sit</ex> on a sofa, on a
chair, or on the ground</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And he came and took the book put of the right hand of him that
<qex>sate</qex> upon the seat.</q> <rj><qau>Bible (1551) (Rev. v.
7.)</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I pray you, jest, sir, as you <qex>sit</qex> at dinner.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To perch; to rest with the feet drawn up, as birds
do on a branch, pole, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To remain in a state of repose; to rest; to abide;
to rest in any position or condition.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And Moses said to . . . the children of Reuben, Shall your
brethren go to war, and shall ye <qex>sit</qex> here?</q> <rj><qau>Num.
xxxii. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like a demigod here <qex>sit</qex> I in the sky.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To lie, rest, or bear; to press or weigh; -- with
<xex>on</xex>; <as>as, a weight or burden <ex>sits</ex> lightly upon
him</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The calamity <qex>sits</qex> heavy on us.</q> <rj><qau>Jer.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To be adjusted; to fit; <as>as, a coat <ex>sits</ex>
well or ill</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This new and gorgeous garment, majesty,⟦br⟧
<qex>Sits</qex> not so easy on me as you think.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To suit one well or ill, as an act; to become; to
befit; -- used impersonally.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To cover and warm eggs for hatching, as a fowl; to
brood; to incubate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As the partridge <qex>sitteth</qex> on eggs, and hatcheth them
not.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. xvii. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To have position, as at the point blown from; to
hold a relative position; to have direction.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like a good miller that knows how to grind, which way soever the
wind <qex>sits</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Selden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Sits</qex> the wind in that quarter?</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>To occupy a place or seat as a member of an official
body; <as>as, to <ex>sit</ex> in Congress</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>To hold a session; to be in session for official
business; -- said of legislative assemblies, courts, etc.; <as>as, the
court <ex>sits</ex> in January; the aldermen <ex>sit</ex>
to-night</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>To take a position for the purpose of having some
artistic representation of one's self made, as a picture or a bust;
<as>as, to <ex>sit</ex> to a painter</as>.</def> <-- sit for seems more
common now -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To sit at</b></col>, <cd>to rest under; to be subject
to.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧A farmer can not husband his ground
so well if he <xex>sit at</xex> a great rent⟦rdquo⟧. <au>Bacon.</au> --
<mcol><col><b>To sit at meat</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To sit at
table</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to be at table for eating.</cd> --
<col><b>To sit down</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To place one's self on a
chair or other seat; <as>as, <ex>to sit down</ex> when tired</as>.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To begin a siege; <as>as, the enemy <ex>sat down</ex>
before the town</as>.</cd> <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To settle; to fix a
permanent abode</cd>. <au>Spenser.</au> <sd>(d)</sd> <cd>To rest; to
cease as satisfied.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Here we can not <xex>sit down</xex>, but
still proceed in our search.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Rogers.</au> -- <col><b>To sit
for a fellowship</b></col>, <cd>to offer one's self for examination with
a view to obtaining a fellowship.</cd> <mark>[Eng. Univ.]</mark> --
<col><b>To sit out</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To be without engagement
or employment</cd>. <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Bp. Sanderson.</au>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To outstay.</cd> <sd>(c)</sd> <cd>to refrain from
participating in [an activity such as a dance or hand at cards]; used
especially after one has recently participated in an earlier such
activity. The one sitting out does not necessarily have to sit during
the activity foregone.</cd> -- <col><b>To sit under</b></col>, <cd>to be
under the instruction or ministrations of; as, <ex>to sit under</ex> a
preacher; <ex>to sit under</ex> good preaching.</cd> -- <col><b>To sit
up</b></col>, <cd>to rise from, or refrain from, a recumbent posture or
from sleep; to sit with the body upright; as, <ex>to sit up</ex> late at
night; also, to watch; <as>as, <ex>to sit up</ex> with a sick
person</as>.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧He that was dead <xex>sat up</xex>, and began
to speak.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Luke vii. 15.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sit
<hw>Sit</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To sit
upon; to keep one's seat upon; <as>as, he <ex>sits</ex> a horse
well</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hardly the muse can <qex>sit</qex> the headstrong horse.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cause to be seated or in a sitting posture; to
furnish a seat to; -- used reflexively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>sat</qex> them down to weep.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Sit</qex> you down, father; rest you.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To suit (well <it>or</it> ill); to become.</def>
<mark>[Obs. or R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Site</ent>⟦br⟧
